Chapter 6 Distance¶

In multivariate analysis and machine learning, distance (or dissimilarity) is a fundamental concept used to quantify how different two observations (points, vectors, or probability distributions) are from one another.
A distance measure allows us to compare data points in high-dimensional space, serving as the foundation for many algorithms such as clustering (e.g., k-means), nearest neighbor classification, multidimensional scaling, and manifold learning.

Let

$$ \mathbf{x}_1 = (x_{11}, x_{12}, \cdots, x_{1p})^{T}, \quad \mathbf{x}_2 = (x_{21}, x_{22}, \cdots, x_{2p})^{T} $$

represent two observations in a $p$-dimensional feature space.
The distance between $\mathbf{x}_1$ and $\mathbf{x}_2$ captures the magnitude of their difference across all dimensions.

Euclidean Distance¶

The most common and intuitive measure of distance is the Euclidean distance, also known as the $L_2$ distance:

$$ \|\mathbf{x}_1 - \mathbf{x}_2\|_2 = \sqrt{(\mathbf{x}_1 - \mathbf{x}_2)^T (\mathbf{x}_1 - \mathbf{x}_2)} = \sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^{p} (x_{1i} - x_{2i})^2} $$

This represents the straight-line (geometric) distance between two points in $p$-dimensional space and satisfies the key properties of a metric:

  1. Non-negativity: $d(\mathbf{x}_1, \mathbf{x}_2) \ge 0$
  2. Identity: $d(\mathbf{x}_1, \mathbf{x}_2) = 0$ if and only if $\mathbf{x}_1 = \mathbf{x}_2$
  3. Symmetry: $d(\mathbf{x}_1, \mathbf{x}_2) = d(\mathbf{x}_2, \mathbf{x}_1)$
  4. Triangle inequality: $d(\mathbf{x}_1, \mathbf{x}_3) \le d(\mathbf{x}_1, \mathbf{x}_2) + d(\mathbf{x}_2, \mathbf{x}_3)$

Euclidean distance is widely used in algorithms that assume data are continuous and features are comparably scaled.

Manhattan Distance ($L_1$ Distance)¶

The Manhattan distance, also known as the city-block or taxicab distance, is based on the absolute differences between coordinates:

$$ \|\mathbf{x}_1 - \mathbf{x}_2\|_1 = \sum_{i=1}^{p} |x_{1i} - x_{2i}| = |x_{11} - x_{21}| + |x_{12} - x_{22}| + \cdots + |x_{1p} - x_{2p}| $$

This distance measures the path one would travel along grid lines (like streets in Manhattan) rather than as the crow flies.
It is more robust to outliers than Euclidean distance and often used when features represent counts or ordinal data.

Maximum (Chebyshev) Distance ($L_{\infty}$ Distance)¶

The maximum distance (or Chebyshev distance) focuses on the largest coordinate difference:

$$ \|\mathbf{x}_1 - \mathbf{x}_2\|_{\infty} = \max_i |x_{1i} - x_{2i}| $$

This measure is useful in cases where we care about the worst-case difference between two vectors, such as in tolerance-based or quality-control applications.

Minkowski Distance¶

The Minkowski distance generalizes all the above forms and is defined as:

$$ D_{12} = \left( \sum_{i=1}^{p} |x_{1i} - x_{2i}|^{r} \right)^{1/r} $$

where $r \ge 1$ is a parameter:

  • $r = 1$ Manhattan distance
  • $r = 2$ Euclidean distance
  • $r \to \infty$ Maximum distance

Thus, Minkowski distance provides a flexible framework that allows different sensitivity to large versus small differences among coordinates.

Hellinger Distance (for Probability Distributions)¶

For comparing probability distributions, distance must be defined differently.
Given two discrete probability distributions $P = (p_1, p_2, \ldots, p_n)$ and $Q = (q_1, q_2, \ldots, q_n)$, the Hellinger distance is defined as:

$$ H(P, Q) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \sqrt{ \sum_{i=1}^{n} \left( \sqrt{p_i} - \sqrt{q_i} \right)^2 } $$

Hellinger distance takes values in $[0, 1]$, where:

  • $H(P, Q) = 0$ indicates identical distributions
  • $H(P, Q) = 1$ indicates completely disjoint distributions

It is especially useful in information theory, Bayesian inference, and machine learning when comparing probability models.

Examples¶

Example 1:
Determine the Euclidean distance between
$$P = (2, 3, 4, 2, 5), \quad Q = (1, -2, 1, 3, 3)$$

Example 2:
Find the Manhattan distance between
$$P = (2, 3, 4, 2, 5), \quad Q = (1, -2, 1, 3, 3)$$

Mahalanobis Distance¶

The Mahalanobis distance is a powerful generalization of the Euclidean distance that accounts for the correlations among variables and the scale of the data. While the Euclidean distance treats each variable equally and assumes independence, the Mahalanobis distance measures distance in terms of standardized and decorrelated units.

Intuitively, the Mahalanobis distance can be interpreted as the distance between two standardized vectors in a multivariate space, where standardization is based on the datas covariance structure.
If variables are correlated or have different variances, this distance automatically adjusts for these effects.

In other words:

  • When the covariance matrix $\Sigma$ is the identity matrix, the Mahalanobis distance reduces to the Euclidean distance.
  • When features are correlated or have different scales, $\Sigma^{-1}$ rescales and rotates the space to compute distances appropriately.

For two $p$-dimensional vectors $\mathbf{x}$ and $\mathbf{y}$:

$$ D_M(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{y}) = \sqrt{(\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{y})^T \Sigma^{-1} (\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{y})} $$

where

  • $\Sigma$ is the covariance matrix of the underlying distribution

Comments¶

  • Mahalanobis distance considers both variances and covariances in the data.
  • Mahalanobis distance provides a scale-invariant and correlation-aware measure of dissimilarity between multivariate observations.

Example¶

Let
$$ \mathbf{X} = (4, 3), \quad \mathbf{Y} = (1, 7) $$

and suppose the covariance matrix of the underlying bivariate distribution is a diagonal matrix:

$$ \Sigma = \begin{pmatrix} 4 & 0 \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} $$

Find the Mahalanobis distance.

In [9]:
#Find the Mahalanobis Distance
x = c(4,3)
y = c(1,7)

#S = matrix(c(4,0,0,1),nrow=2 )

S= diag(c(4,1))
S

#Find the Mahalanobis Distance between X and Y, given the covariance matrix
d = sqrt( t(x-y)%*% solve(S)%*% (x-y)  )

The Distance Matrix¶

In multivariate analysis and clustering, a distance matrix (or dissimilarity matrix) summarizes the pairwise distances among all observations in a dataset.
Each entry in the matrix quantifies how far apart two observations are according to a chosen distance metric (e.g., Euclidean, Manhattan, or Mahalanobis distance).

Definition¶

A distance matrix is a nonnegative, square, and symmetric matrix whose $(i, j)$-th element represents the distance between the $i$-th and $j$-th observations:

$$ D = [d_{ij}]_{n \times n}, \quad \text{where } d_{ij} = \text{distance}(\mathbf{x}_i, \mathbf{x}_j) $$

Key properties:

  1. Non-negativity: $d_{ij} \ge 0$
  2. Symmetry: $d_{ij} = d_{ji}$
  3. Diagonal elements: $d_{ii} = 0$
  4. Triangle inequality: $d_{ij} \le d_{ik} + d_{kj}$ (for metric distances)

Thus, the matrix has the general form:

$$ D = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & d_{12} & d_{13} & \cdots & d_{1n} \\ d_{21} & 0 & d_{23} & \cdots & d_{2n} \\ d_{31} & d_{32} & 0 & \cdots & d_{3n} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ d_{n1} & d_{n2} & d_{n3} & \cdots & 0 \end{pmatrix} $$

Number of Pairwise Distances¶

If we have $n$ data points (observations), the number of unique pairwise distances** (excluding self-distances) is:

$$ \text{Number of pairs} = \frac{n(n-1)}{2} $$

For example:

  • If $n = 5$, then there are
    $$ \frac{5(5-1)}{2} = 10 $$ unique pairwise distances.

(Note: 25 includes self-distances and duplicates the true unique distances are 10.)

Example¶

Suppose we have 5 data points, each represented by a 6-dimensional feature vector.
We can compute the pairwise distances (e.g., Euclidean) between every pair of points to form the distance matrix.

Example: Using the Sparrow Bird Data¶

Lets compute the distance matrix for the Sparrow dataset of all observations. In R, this can be done using the dist() function.

Distance Based on Proportions¶

When variables represent counts across categories (such as the number of individuals in each species, or counts of words, etc.), it is often useful to convert them into proportions or percentages for distance calculation.

A proportion $p$ is a decimal between 0 and 1, representing the relative amount of a category.
For example, the proportion of birds that survived could be 0.73, meaning 73% survival rate.

Transforming Count Data¶

Distances for count or proportion data begin with transforming each row of count data into relative counts:

$$ p_{ij} = \frac{x_{ij}}{\sum_{k=1}^{K} x_{ik}} $$

so that each row (observation) sums to 1.
This normalization ensures that comparisons between rows are based on relative composition, not absolute magnitude.

1. Total Variation (TV) or $L_1/2$ Distance¶

This is the most commonly used measure for proportion (or percentage) data.
It is also equivalent to the BrayCurtis distance when applied to normalized rows.

$$ d_1(\mathbf{p}, \mathbf{q}) = \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i=1}^{K} |p_i - q_i| $$

Properties:

  • $0 \le d_1 \le 1$
  • Interpretable as the minimum amount of probability mass that must be moved to make $\mathbf{p}$ identical to $\mathbf{q}$.
  • Reduces to the same value as the BrayCurtis dissimilarity when data are expressed as proportions.

2. Bray–Curtis Distance¶

The BrayCurtis distance (also known as the dissimilarity index) is one of the most widely used metrics for ecological and compositional data.

Formula for raw counts:

Given two samples $\mathbf{x} = (x_1, x_2, \dots, x_K)$ and $\mathbf{y} = (y_1, y_2, \dots, y_K)$:

$$ d_{\text{BC}}(\mathbf{x}, \mathbf{y}) = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{K} |x_i - y_i|}{\sum_{i=1}^{K} (x_i + y_i)} $$

If data are proportions (each row sums to 1):

$$ d_{\text{BC}}(\mathbf{p}, \mathbf{q}) = \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i=1}^{K} |p_i - q_i| $$

Thus, for normalized data, the BrayCurtis distance is exactly equal to the Total Variation (TV) or $L_1/2$ distance.

BrayCurtis distance captures differences in relative composition between samples. It is especially appropriate for ecological, microbiome, or environmental datasets where absolute abundance is less important than relative abundance.

Properties:

  • $0 \le d_{\text{BC}} \le 1$
  • $d_{\text{BC}} = 0$ identical compositions
  • $d_{\text{BC}} = 1$ completely distinct compositions
  • Not a true metric (it doesnt satisfy the triangle inequality), but widely used in ecological and environmental data.

The mantel randomization test¶

Mantel (1967) introduced a valuable test for comparing two distance or similarity matrices to address the challenge of identifying spatial and temporal clustering of diseases. This test aims to test whether instances of a disease occurring close in space also exhibit proximity in time.

Mantel tests are correlation analyses that evaluate the correlation between two matrices rather than two individual variables. A significant Mantel test indicates a positive correlation between the distances in one matrix and those in the other. Consequently, as the distance between samples increases in one matrix, it tends to increase in the other matrix as well.

Examples: The Mantel test finds common application in ecology, particularly with data representing estimates of "distance" between objects like species of organisms. For instance, one matrix may comprise estimates of genetic distances, reflecting the dissimilarities between different genomes of species obtained through molecular systematics methods. Meanwhile, another matrix could contain estimates of geographical distances between the ranges of each species relative to every other species. The hypothesis under examination in this scenario is whether the genetic variation among these organisms correlates with the geographical distance.

#The purpose is to see if the distance in the pollution (ozone) level and the geographical distance are related or not.
#We can use Mantel test 

#distance objects returned by dist function
g.dist = dist(cbind(ozone$Lon, ozone$Lat))
ozone.dist = dist(ozone$Av8top)

set.seed(217)
# class 'dist' expected in the input
mantel.rtest(g.dist, ozone.dist, nrepet = 9000)

#Simulated p-value: 0.03199644 
#Reject H0 (not related).  There is sufficient evidence in the data to
#support H1 that the distance in ozone is related to the geographical distance.

#between the matrix entries. Thus,smaller differences in ozone are generally observed among pairs of
#stations that are closer to each other than those farther apart.

Multivariate outliers¶

Outliers are data points that deviate significantly from the general pattern exhibited by the rest of the data. These points lie outside the normal range of the dataset. To detect outliers, the Mahalanobis distance is calculated for each data point relative to the center of the multivariate data set (to the center of the closest group). These calculated squared Mahalanobis distances are then compared with a $\chi^2$ distribution with degrees of freedom $p$ (the number of variables).

Example: Determine any outliers using all quantative variables of the sparrow data.

2. Using the sample covariance of all quantitative variables as the covariance matrix,¶

calculate the squared Mahalanobis distance between all observations and the center¶

(the mean vector of all observations). Calculate the p-value for each Mahalanobis distance.¶

Identify any outliers if the p-value is below 0.01 and report the number of outliers.¶

#Load the data

#If all data are from a group, ...

loc1 ="~//distribute_files//data//Bumpus_sparrows.csv"
sparrow1.dat = read.csv( loc1,  header = 1 )
head(sparrow1.dat)

#Data matrix
dat = sparrow1.dat[, -1]

#Step 1 : calculate the Manhanobis distance to the center of the data
mean.vec = colMeans(dat)
#mean.vec
cov.dat = cov(dat)

#squared mahalanobis distance
dist.vec = mahalanobis(dat, center=mean.vec, cov= cov.dat)

#hist(dist.vec)
#If the data are from a multivariate normal , the distribution of squared mahalanobis distance has a Chisq distribution 
#with the degrees of freedom = the number of variables.

#If the level of sigificance = 0.01, if p-value of an observation is below the level of sigificance, 
#then it is identified as an outlier based on this method.

#P( Chisq distribution > the observed distance) 
pval.vect = 1 -  pchisq( dist.vec, df= 5 )
round(pval.vect, 5)

#The number of outliers at the significnace level of 0.01
sum(pval.vect < 0.01)

#See which is (are) outliers
dat[pval.vect < 0.01, ]

#The 31th observation is an outler :  162, 239, 30.3, 18, 23.1
